The [[Royal Australian Air Force]] (RAAF) operates eight [[Boeing C-17 Globemaster III]] large transport aircraft. Four C-17s were ordered in mid-2006 to improve the [[Australian Defence Force|Australian Defence Force's]] (ADF's) ability to operate outside Australia and its region. The aircraft entered service between November 2006 and January 2008, the second pair being delivered ahead of schedule. Two more Globemasters were ordered in 2011, the sixth being delivered to the RAAF in November 2012. Another two C-17s were ordered in October 2014, with the final aircraft being delivered in November 2015. The Globemasters are built to the same specifications as those operated by the [[United States Air Force]] (USAF), and the Australian aircraft are maintained through an international contract with Boeing.

All of the RAAF's Globemasters are assigned to [[No. 36 Squadron RAAF|No. 36 Squadron]] and are based at [[RAAF Base Amberley]] in Queensland. The aircraft have supported ADF operations in Afghanistan, Iraq and other locations in the Middle East, as well as training exercises in Australia and the United States. They have also transported supplies and personnel as part of relief efforts following natural disasters in Australia, Japan, New Zealand and several other countries. The C-17s are highly regarded throughout the Australian military for their ability to carry large amounts of cargo across long distances, and the process through which they were acquired has been identified as an example of good practice in defence procurement.

==Acquisition==

===Selection===
The RAAF began considering options for heavy transport aircraft to provide a [[strategic airlift]] capability during the early 2000s. This investigation was initiated after the ADF [[INTERFET|deployment to East Timor]] in 1999 and [[Operation Slipper|operations in the Middle East]] from 2001 revealed shortcomings in the RAAF's ability to transport the increasingly large and heavy vehicles and other items of equipment used by the Australian Army. To support these operations, the ADF found that it needed long-ranged aircraft capable of carrying larger loads than could be accommodated in the RAAF's [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules in Australian service|force of Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] transports. As a result of this capability gap, the ADF needed to use USAF transports and chartered Russian-built commercial heavy lift aircraft to move supplies and equipment from Australia to its forces in Afghanistan and the Middle East. This experience proved frustrating, as both categories of aircraft were often not available and the commercial transports were expensive to lease.{{sfn|Thomson|2007|p=184}}{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|pp=20–21}} The crash of a civil-chartered [[Ilyushin Il-76]] in East Timor in 2003 also raised concerns within the ADF about the safety of the Russian transport aircraft.{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=21}} Following advocacy from the military, the Australian Government announced as part of an update to its national security strategy in December 2005 that it would consider acquiring heavy lift aircraft to supplement the RAAF's [[Lockheed Martin C-130J Super Hercules]] transports.{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=21}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Australia's National Security: Defence Update 2005|url=http://www.defence.gov.au/oscdf/ans/2005/|work=Media release|publisher=Department of Defence|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> This initiative was one of several measures announced in the government's ''Defence Update 2005'' paper, which sought to better prepare the ADF to operate in locations distant from Australia.{{sfn|Thomson|2006|p=2}}

In early 2006 a project office was established within the [[Defence Materiel Organisation]] (DMO) to evaluate the options for acquiring heavy lift aircraft. The office considered the Boeing C-17 Globemaster III, which was in service with the USAF at the time, as well as the [[Airbus A400M Atlas]], which was yet to make its first flight. Boeing aggressively marketed the C-17 to the Australian Government during this period.{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=21}} Though unstated, commonality with the USAF and the United Kingdom's RAF was also considered advantageous.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2008|p=42}} In March 2006, Minister for Defence [[Brendan Nelson]] announced that the government had decided to purchase three C-17s and take out an option for a fourth.{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=21}} Nelson also announced that the C-17s would be operated by [[No. 36 Squadron RAAF]], which was to transfer its C-130H Hercules to [[No. 37 Squadron RAAF|No. 37 Squadron]] and relocate from [[RAAF Base Richmond]] in New South Wales to RAAF Base Amberley in Queensland.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2008|pp=41–42}} Amberley was selected over Richmond as the base for the Globemasters as its runways and engineering facilities were better able to support large aircraft.{{sfn|Thomson|2007|p=184}}

The government exercised the option to purchase a fourth C-17 between the time this announcement was made and the signing of the final contract on 31 July 2006. The total cost of the four aircraft was $A821 million, and Boeing also received an A$85 million contract to allow Australia to join the "virtual fleet" global C-17 sustainment program.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2008|p=42}} Additional funding was allocated to build headquarters and maintenance facilities at Amberley as well as to upgrade the air movements facilities at RAAF Bases [[RAAF Base Darwin|Darwin]], [[RAAF Base Edinburgh|Edinburgh]], [[RAAF Base Townsville|Townsville]], and [[RAAF Base Pearce|Pearce]].<ref name="On Time" /> The package of funding needed to purchase and introduce the Globemasters into service was provided as a supplement to the government's long-term defence funding program, so the ADF did not have to forgo any other planned capabilities.{{sfn|Thomson|2006|p=2}} The C-17s were acquired through the United States Government's [[Foreign Military Sales]] program, meaning that they were first delivered to the USAF and then transferred to the RAAF.{{sfn|Thomson|2007|p=184}} The USAF provided some of the C-17 delivery "slots" it had purchased to the RAAF to enable the type to rapidly enter Australian service, making them identical to American C-17 even in paint scheme, the only difference being the [[Military aircraft insignia|national marking]]s. This allowed delivery to commence within nine months of commitment to the program.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2008|p=42}}<ref name=awst_20061211>"Stock Standard". ''[[Aviation Week & Space Technology]]'', 11 December 2006.</ref>

===Delivery and sustainment===

The RAAF received its first four C-17s between late 2006 and early 2008. The initial aircraft, which was allocated the [[serial number]] A41-206, was completed in October 2006 and arrived in Australia on 4 December that year.{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=21}} A welcome ceremony attended by Prime Minister [[John Howard]], Nelson and other dignitaries was held at [[Fairbairn, Canberra|Defence Establishment Fairbairn]] in Canberra.<ref name="master has arrived">{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Phil|title=The master has arrived|url=http://www.defence.gov.au/news/raafnews/editions/4823/topstories/story01.htm|accessdate=26 May 2013|newspaper=Air Force|date=14 December 2006}}</ref> The second aircraft, A41-207, was delivered on 11 May 2007. A41-208 was handed over to the RAAF on 18 December 2007, and A41-209 was accepted on 18 January 2008.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2008|p=42}} The first two aircraft were delivered in accordance with the expected schedule, and the third and fourth were each delivered two months early. The RAAF also acquired a C-17 flight simulator, which entered service in January 2010.{{sfn|ANAO|2012|p=327}} In the 2012–13 edition of its annual ''Major Projects Report'', the [[Australian National Audit Office]] judged that a lesson for the Australian Government from the successful procurement of the first four Globemasters was that purchasing major equipment on an "off-the-shelf" basis allows "considerable acceleration of the standard acquisition cycle".{{sfn|ANAO|2012|p=331}} Similarly, [[Australian Strategic Policy Institute]] analyst Mark Thomson wrote in 2008 that "the breakneck speed with which the C-17 acquisition was executed (and the good outcomes of the acquisition) provides an example of what can be achieved" through off-the-shelf purchasing, and that such projects generally deliver better outcomes for the ADF than attempts to develop equipment tailored to Australia's needs.{{sfn|Thomson|2008|pp=162–163}}
[[File:RAAF (A41-206) C-17A Globemaster III on display at the 2013 Avalon Airshow.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Colour photo of a grey military aircraft on the tarmac of an airport with people in casual clothes walking in front of it.|A41-206, the RAAF's first C-17, on display at the 2013 [[Australian International Airshow]]]]

The Australian Government ordered a further two C-17s during 2011 and 2012. In February 2011 Minister for Defence [[Stephen Smith (Australian politician)|Stephen Smith]] announced that another C-17 would be purchased for a cost of $A130 million. This aircraft was ordered to prevent a shortfall of airlift capacity while the original four C-17s underwent scheduled [[Aircraft maintenance checks#D Check|heavy maintenance]].{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=22}} The decision to purchase this aircraft also supplanted an earlier plan to acquire two more C-130Js.<ref name="Fifth RAAF C-17 flies">{{cite news|title=Fifth RAAF C-17 flies|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2011/08/fifth-raaf-c-17-flies/|accessdate=13 July 2013|newspaper=Australian Aviation|date=29 August 2011}}</ref> As the deadline for A41-206 to be temporarily taken out of service for maintenance was rapidly approaching, the USAF agreed to transfer a C-17 airframe that was nearing completion to the RAAF. This aircraft was delivered on 14 September 2011, and arrived in Australia nine days later. At the ceremony held to welcome A41-210, Smith announced that the government intended to order another C-17.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2011|p=21}} The $A160 million contract for this aircraft was signed in March 2012,{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=22}} and it was delivered to the RAAF on 1 November that year.<ref name="Sixth C-17 touches down">{{cite web|title=Sixth C-17 touches down|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2012/11/sixth-c-17-touches-down/|work=Australian Aviation|accessdate=16 January 2013|date=8 November 2012}}</ref> Funding for these two aircraft was obtained through a combination of supplements to the Defence budget and reallocating unspent funds from ADF projects running behind schedule.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2011|p=21}}

Owing to budget constraints and the scheduled closure of Boeing's Globemaster production line in 2015, it was considered unlikely in 2012 that the RAAF would acquire more Globemasters.{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=22}} However, in August 2014 Minister for Defence [[David Johnston (politician)|David Johnston]] stated that the Government was likely to purchase a further one or two C-17s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prime Minister Tony Abbott to fly worldwide non-stop on Airbus KC-30A|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/prime-minister-tony-abbott-to-fly-worldwide-nonstop-on-airbus-kc30a/story-fncynjr2-1227023370734|accessdate=14 August 2014|work=News.com.au|date=20 August 2014}}</ref> The Government announced that it would purchase two Globemasters in October 2014, and requested information on the pricing and availability for a further pair of aircraft.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two extra C-17s confirmed, two further aircraft under consideration|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2014/10/australia-seeks-two-extra-c-17s/|accessdate=3 October 2014|work=Australian Aviation|date=3 October 2014}}</ref> In November 2014 Australia lodged a formal request with the United States [[Defense Security Cooperation Agency]] for four C-17s and associated equipment, for a total cost of $A1.85 billion.<ref name="Formal request made for extra C-17s">{{cite news|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Andrew|title=Formal request made for extra RAAF C-17s|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2014/11/defence-c-17-story/|accessdate=15 November 2014|work=Australian Aviation|date=13 November 2014}}</ref> An order for the RAAF's seventh and eighth Globemasters was formally announced by Prime Minister [[Tony Abbott]] on 10&nbsp;April 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-04-10/raaf-to-receive-two-more-c-17-globemasters-billion-dollar/6384104|last=Greene|first=Andrew|title=RAAF to receive two more C-17 Globemaster planes in billion-dollar defence purchase|date=11 April 2015|accessdate=12 April 2015|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref> The first of the new C-17s arrived in Australia on 29 July 2015, and the second on 4 November that year. These two aircraft were among the last C-17s to have been built before the production line was closed, and it is not expected that the RAAF will acquire more Globemasters.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Waldron|first1=Greg|title=Australia receives seventh C-17|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/australia-receives-seventh-c-17-415144/|accessdate=30 July 2015|work=Flightglobal|date=29 July 2015}}</ref><ref name="Eighth and final RAAF C-17 delivered">{{cite news|title=Eighth and final RAAF C-17 delivered|accessdate=16 November 2015|work=Australian Aviation|date=4 November 2014|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2015/11/eighth-and-final-raaf-c-17-delivered/}}</ref> It was reported in December 2014 that the New Zealand Government was considering purchasing between two and four Globemasters, and ''Australian Aviation'' journalist Andrew McLaughlin suggested that any such acquisition would build on Australia's C-17 support infrastructure.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Andrew|title=Reports: NZ considering C-17 acquisition|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2014/12/reports-nz-considering-c-17-acquisition/|accessdate=29 December 2014|work=Australian Aviation|date=22 December 2014}}</ref> The New Zealand Government ultimately decided to not purchase any Globemasters.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cowlishaw|first1=Shane|title=Plans to replace Defence Force's 'rusting' Hercules fleet fails to get lift off|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/74849069/Plans-to-replace-Defence-Forces-rusting-Hercules-fleet-fails-to-get-lift-off|accessdate=26 June 2016|work=stuff|date=13 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Consideration of a C-17 Air Transport Capability|url=http://www.defence.govt.nz/reports-publications/consideration-of-c17-capability.html|publisher=New Zealand Ministry of Defence|accessdate=9 July 2016}}</ref>

Maintenance of the Australian Globemasters is undertaken by both the RAAF and Boeing. As part of Australia's membership of the Globemaster III Sustainment Partnership, Air Force technicians are responsible for routine servicing and Boeing handles major maintenance tasks. Boeing also provides technical support for RAAF Globemasters during deployments outside of Australia, and the company is paid in return for achieving contractually mandated aircraft availability targets.<ref>{{cite news|title=RAAF signs for C-17 support, as fears grow for the production line|url=http://www.australiandefence.com.au/E04AE5C0-F806-11DD-8DFE0050568C22C9|accessdate=8 April 2013|newspaper=Australian Defence Magazine|date=1 October 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Boeing delivers sixth C-17|url=http://www.australiandefence.com.au/news/boeing-delivers-sixth-c-17|accessdate=8 April 2013|newspaper=Australian Defence Magazine|date=2 November 2012}}</ref> Due to the [[economies of scale]] arising from a large international maintenance program, the contract with Boeing is considered to be cheaper than attempting to support the aircraft through unique Australian contracts.{{sfn|Thomson|2007|p=185}} It is expected that the RAAF's Globemasters will remain in service for 30 years.{{sfn|Thomson|2007|p=185}}

{{Quote_box
|width=32%
|align=right
|quote=Because you can put the engines into reverse thrust while airborne [a definite no-no in most large jets] you know you can just drop out of the sky. The rates of descent and the rates of climb it has are just great.
|source=—Flight Lieutenant Samantha Fairbairn, No. 36 Squadron, on the C-17{{sfn|McPhedran|2011|pp=228–231}}
}}
The ADF and defence commentators have judged that the Globemaster acquisition has significantly increased the RAAF's airlift capabilities. The aircraft have a maximum range of {{convert|10389|km}} and are capable of operating from short and unsealed airstrips. Each Globemaster can carry up to {{convert|77519|kg}} of cargo, and the large size of the aircraft means that it can accommodate [[outsize cargo|outsize items]]. Maximum loads include 102&nbsp;passengers, 36&nbsp;personnel on stretchers, an [[M1 Abrams]] tank, three [[Eurocopter Tiger]] helicopters or five [[Bushmaster Protected Mobility Vehicle]]s.<ref>Pittaway (2012), pp. 19–20</ref><ref name="RAAF_website_C-17">{{cite web|title=C-17A Globemaster Description and Specifications|url=http://www.airforce.gov.au/Technology/Aircraft/C-17A_Globemaster/?RAAF-h0719xJ/eXjMFO8eLULT2D7U+C9pXnFB|publisher=Royal Australian Air Force|accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref> These are much larger loads than can be transported by the Air Force's C-130 Hercules transports, and the RAAF website states that each C-17 can carry three times as much cargo as a C-130.<ref name=RAAF_website_C-17 /> Flown with a joystick and [[fly-by-wire]] controls, the C-17 is also highly manoeuvrable and responsive considering its size.{{sfn|McPhedran|2011|pp=228–231}} [[Ian McPhedran]], the defence correspondent for [[News Corp Australia]], judged that the C-17s have "changed the game" for the RAAF by allowing the force to rapidly transport large amounts of cargo into combat zones.{{sfn|McPhedran|2011|pp=271–272}} According to aviation journalist Nigel Pittaway, the Globemaster's capabilities have made it a highly regarded asset throughout the [[Australian Defence Organisation]].{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=19}}

==Operational service==

===Training and combat operations===
[[File:RAF RAAF USAF C-17s 2007.jpg|thumb|alt=A group of people wearing overalls standing together in front of three large grey aircraft.|Australian, British and United States C-17 Globemasters and aircrew in Britain during June 2007]]
Ahead of the delivery of Australia's first C-17s, RAAF personnel received training on the aircraft in the United States. From May 2006 a group of pilots and [[loadmaster]]s led by Wing Commander [[Linda Corbould]], the commanding officer designate of No. 36 Squadron, undertook conversion training with the USAF's C-17 units at [[Altus Air Force Base]] and [[Joint Base Charleston|Charleston Air Force Base]]. A group of 48 technical personnel also received training at Charleston and [[Joint Base Lewis-McChord|McChord Air Force Base]] from September that year.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2008|p=42}} No. 36 Squadron began a period of intensive training once Corbould delivered A41-206 to Amberley on 7 December 2006, and the unit achieved initial operating capability status in September 2007.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2008|p=42}}<ref name="On Time">{{cite web|title=Air Force's C-17 Fleet Complete&nbsp;– On Time, On Budget|url=http://www.defence.gov.au/media/DepartmentalTpl.cfm?CurrentId=7487|work=Media release|publisher=Department of Defence|accessdate=16 January 2013|date=9 March 2008}}{{dead link|date=November 2016}}</ref> Also in 2007, the RAAF's [[No. 1 Air Operations Support Squadron RAAF|No. 1 Air Operations Support Squadron]] was expanded by 80 personnel to provide air load teams to support the Globemasters.{{sfn|O'Brien|2009|p=214}} A project to acquire the equipment needed to allow the RAAF's C-17s to be used in the [[aeromedical evacuation]] role and develop associated crew procedures began in late 2007. The first Globemaster aeromedical evacuation sortie was flown on 5 September 2008, the day after the type was certified to operate in this role.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rollings|first=Barry|title=AME role confirmed|url=http://www.defence.gov.au/news/raafnews/editions/5019/5019.pdf|accessdate=14 July 2013|newspaper=Air Force|date=16 October 2008|page=3}}</ref> On 8 December 2008, Corbould led the RAAF's first all-female aircrew during a training flight over South East Queensland to mark the second anniversary of the entry of the Globemaster into service.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bedo|first=Stephanie|title=Misses master a RAAF monster|url=http://www.goldcoast.com.au/article/2008/12/09/29865_gold-coast-lead-story.html|accessdate=26 May 2013|newspaper=goldcoast.com.au|date=9 December 2008}}</ref> A team of USAF trainers was posted to Amberley until the RAAF had sufficient C-17 pilots who were qualified to instruct others.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2008|p=42}} The RAAF began training new C-17 pilots in early 2010 after the flight simulator was delivered, and the first Australian-trained pilots graduated in early May that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=RAAF C-17 pilot training begins in Australia|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2010/02/raaf-c-17-pilot-training-begins-in-australia/|accessdate=19 January 2013|newspaper=Australian Aviation|date=8 February 2010}}</ref><ref name="First Australian trained">{{cite news|title=First Australian trained C-17 pilots graduate|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2010/06/first-australian-trained-c-17-pilots-graduate/|accessdate=19 January 2013|newspaper=Australian Aviation|date=3 June 2010}}</ref> No. 36 Squadron achieved final operating capability status in December 2011.{{sfn|ANAO|2012|p=323}} The components for a simulated C-17 cargo compartment were delivered to Amberley in early 2013, and this facility was commissioned in November that year. The simulator is used to train air movements and medical staff as well as to develop and trial new cargo carrying techniques for the C-17s.<ref>{{cite news|last=Perks|first=Michelle|title=C-17 trainer nears completion|url=http://airforcenews.realviewdigital.com/?iid=79706#folio=8|accessdate=7 August 2013|newspaper=Air Force|date=1 August 2013|page=9}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Commissioning of C-17A Cargo Compartment Trainer|url=http://news.defence.gov.au/2013/11/22/commissioning-of-c-17a-cargo-compartment-trainer/|work=Media release|publisher=Department of Defence|accessdate=26 November 2013}}</ref> The first Australian trained Globemaster loadmasters graduated in mid-2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hamilton|first1=Eamon|title=Aussie-trained loadies|url=http://airforcenews.realviewdigital.com/#folio=6|accessdate=14 July 2014|work=Air Force|date=17 July 2014|page=7}}</ref>

The RAAF's Globemasters have supported Australian military deployments worldwide. The [[Air Mobility Control Centre RAAF|Air Mobility Control Centre]] manages the tasking of the Globemasters, and tries to allocate them to missions for which they are the most cost-effective option.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Eamon|title=Finding right fit for job|url=http://digital.realviewtechnologies.com/?xml=defencenews_airforce.xml&iid=65895&startpage=11&crd=0&searchKey=Air%20Mobility%20Control%20Centre|accessdate=6 April 2013|newspaper=Air Force|date=2 August 2012}}</ref> As of September 2008, No. 36 Squadron was conducting fortnightly flights to transport supplies from Australia to bases in the Middle East; at this time the supplies were moved into the combat zones in Iraq and Afghanistan using C-130 transports.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2008|p=45}} Direct C-17 flights into the major Australian base at [[Tarinkot|Tarin Kot]] in Afghanistan began in July 2009.{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=21}} As No. 36 Squadron's structure does not enable it to permanently station Globemasters in the Middle East, the usual practice has been for one of the type to carry a load of cargo from Australia and then conduct missions in the region for several days before returning to Amberley.{{sfn|McPhedran|2011|p=272}} In a speech delivered in early 2013, Smith stated that during the previous year the Globemasters had supported operations in the Middle East by flying "60 missions, about 330 hours of flight time, during which the C-17As moved 190 vehicles, 1,800 passengers and over 3,600 tonnes of cargo and conducted 20 aeromedical evacuations".<ref name=Smith_Avalon_opening /> In late 2013 a detachment of two Globemasters, three air crews and many other personnel from No. 36 Squadron was established at [[Al Minhad Air Base]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]]. This detachment was the first time that Australian C-17s had been deployed away from Amberley for more than two weeks, and was established to transport ADF equipment out of Afghanistan as part of the reduction of the Australian force in the country.{{sfn|Hollins|2013a|p=30}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Rickey|first=Chris|title=No slowing down|url=http://airforcenews.realviewdigital.com/?iid=84161#folio=4|accessdate=26 November 2013|newspaper=Air Force|date=21 November 2013|page=5}}</ref> Overall, around 100 Globemaster sorties were conducted to fly equipment out of Tarin Kot between November 2012 and the end of 2013.{{sfn|Hollins|2013b|p=36}} All Australian C-17s that fly into Afghanistan are fitted with a [[LAIRCM|Large Aircraft Infrared Countermeasures]] system for protection against missiles.{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=22}}
[[File:RAAF C-17 Afghanistan.jpg|thumb|left|Alt=Colour photo of a grey military aircraft on a dusty airstrip. A person is standing to the right of the aircraft.|A41-209 in Afghanistan during December 2010]]

In December 2013 one of the Globemasters which was deployed to the Middle East was, along with a RAAF Hercules, tasked with flying peacekeepers into [[South Sudan]] to reinforce the United Nations force there following an [[2013 South Sudanese political crisis|outbreak of fighting]].<ref name="Australia to send aircraft">{{cite news|last=Harrison|first=Dan|title=Australia to send aircraft to South Sudan UN mission|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/australia-to-send-aircraft-to-south-sudan-un-mission-20131226-2zxk4.html|accessdate=28 December 2013|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax Media|date=26 December 2013}}</ref> This airlift was completed in mid-January, by which time the Australian C-17 had made eight flights into South Sudan from [[Brindisi]] in Italy and Djibouti.<ref>{{cite news|title=RAAF completes South Sudan airlift assistance|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2014/01/raaf-completes-south-sudan-airlift-assistance/|accessdate=27 January 2014|newspaper=Australian Aviation|date=14 January 2014}}</ref> During September and December 2014 RAAF Globemasters flew five sorties into Iraq to deliver weapons and ammunition destined for Iraqi forces fighting the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Air Task Group|url=http://www.defence.gov.au/Operations/Okra/ATG.asp|website=Operation Okra|publisher=Department of Defence|accessdate=5 December 2015}}</ref>

C-17s have also supported ADF training. In this role they have moved helicopters and other equipment between Australian bases, and supported training deployments to the United States.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2008|p=45}} In April 2010, members of the [[Australian Army|Australian Army's]] No. 176 (Air Dispatch) Squadron became the first paratroopers to jump from a non-American Globemaster; the type was first used to support training by the Army's [[Parachute Training School (Australian Army)|Parachute Training School]] in June that year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paratroops get the jump on C-17A|url=http://www.defence.gov.au/media/download/2010/apr/20100422/|work=Image Gallery: April 2010|publisher=Department of Defence|accessdate=26 May 2013|date=22 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Australian paratroopers jump into history|url=http://www.boeing.com/Features/2010/09/bds_feat_raaf_c17_09_20_10.html|archiveurl=https://wayback.archive.org/web/20100924081724/http://www.boeing.com/Features/2010/09/bds_feat_raaf_c17_09_20_10.html|archivedate=2010-09-24|work=Feature Story|publisher=Boeing|accessdate=26 May 2013|date=20 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Parachute Training School first jump from a RAAF Globemaster|url=http://www.defence.gov.au/media/download/2010/jun/20100611a/index.htm|work=Image Gallery: June 2010|publisher=Department of Defence|accessdate=26 May 2013|date=11 June 2010}}</ref> A C-17 transported an Army M1 Abrams tank for the first time during a training exercise conducted on 11 May 2012.<ref name="ADF Abrams">{{cite news|title=First flight for ADF Abrams|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2012/05/first-flight-for-adf-abrams/|accessdate=19 January 2013|newspaper=Australian Aviation|date=14 May 2012}}</ref> To mark the arrival of the RAAF's final Globemaster, four of the aircraft flew over Brisbane together on 22 November 2012. Each of the C-17s involved in the flight carried a different type of cargo to showcase the type's capabilities; A41-211 was configured for aeromedical evacuation tasks, another C-17 embarked an Abrams tank, one carried two Tiger helicopters and the fourth was loaded with several Bushmasters.<ref name="big impact">{{cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Eamon|title=Sixth C-17A's big impact|url=http://www.defence.gov.au/news/raafnews/editions/5423/5423.pdf|accessdate=14 July 2013|newspaper=Air Force|date=6 December 2012|page=2}}</ref>

Despite the wide range of tasks which have been assigned to the aircraft, the RAAF is currently not operating its Globemasters in all the roles the type is capable of. For instance, in February 2013 the Air Force was reported to be investigating using C-17s to drop special forces boats as well as supplies to warships.<ref name="Australian airlift comes of age">{{cite news|last=Waldron|first=Greg|title=Australian airlift comes of age|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/in-focus-australian-airlift-comes-of-age-381854/|accessdate=7 July 2013|newspaper=Flightglobal|date=19 February 2013}}</ref> Trials to develop the capacity to refuel RAAF Globemasters in flight from the force's [[Airbus A330 MRTT|Airbus KC-30A Multi Role Tanker Transports]] began in May 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=RAAF KC-30 refuels a RAAF C-17 for the first time|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2016/05/raaf-kc-30-refuels-a-raaf-c-17-for-the-first-time/|accessdate=13 November 2016|work=Australian Aviation|date=6 May 2016}}</ref>

===Humanitarian tasks===

In addition to their military tasks, the C-17s have formed part of the Australian Government's response to natural disasters. In November 2007 a C-17 delivered 27 tonnes of supplies to [[Port Moresby]] in Papua New Guinea following heavy flooding caused by [[Cyclone Guba]]. At the conclusion of [[Operation Papua New Guinea Assist|the ADF response to this disaster]], another C-17 mission was conducted to return Army [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk|Sikorsky S-70A-9 Black Hawks]] to their base at [[Townsville, Queensland|Townsville]].{{sfn|McLaughlin|2008|p=45}} During May 2008 a C-17 flew 31 tonnes of emergency equipment from Australia to [[Yangon]] in Burma following [[Cyclone Nargis]]. Later in the month a RAAF Globemaster transported two [[Aérospatiale SA 330 Puma]] helicopters from South Africa to Thailand, from where the helicopters flew into Burma.{{sfn|McLaughlin|2008|p=45}} On 1 October 2009, C-17s transported supplies and ADF evacuation teams from RAAF Base Richmond to [[Samoa]] following the [[2009 Samoa earthquake and tsunami|earthquake there]]. Two days later another C-17 sortie delivered medical personnel and other specialists to [[Padang]] in Indonesia after the [[2009 Sumatra earthquakes|Sumatra earthquakes]].<ref>{{cite news|title=RAAF responds to regional disasters|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2009/10/raaf-responds-to-regional-disasters/|accessdate=19 January 2013|newspaper=Australian Aviation|date=6 October 2009}}</ref> In August 2010, two C-17s were dispatched to deliver emergency supplies to Pakistan following [[2010 Pakistan floods|widespread flooding]] there.<ref>{{cite news|title=RAAF aircraft to help relief efforts in Pakistan|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-08-11/raaf-aircraft-to-help-relief-efforts-in-pakistan/940832|accessdate=19 January 2013|newspaper=ABC News|date=11 August 2010}}</ref>

No. 36 Squadron was particularly active during 2011.{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=22}} In January that year the squadron had to evacuate two C-17s from Amberley to Richmond when the base was threatened by rising floodwaters during the [[2010–2011 Queensland floods|Queensland floods]]; of the other two Globemasters, one was in the Middle East and the other was undergoing maintenance and could not be flown. The aircraft stranded at Amberley was moved onto high ground during the crisis at the base and escaped without damage.{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=22}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2011|p=20}} The two Richmond-based C-17s subsequently flew over 227 tones of supplies to flood-affected regions of Queensland. When [[Early 2011 Victorian floods|flooding also took place in Victoria]] during January, No. 36 Squadron transported 100,000 sandbags to [[Melbourne]] and flew [[Royal Australian Navy]] personnel and vehicles into the state from [[HMAS Albatross (air station)|HMAS ''Albatross'']] in New South Wales. No. 36 Squadron returned to Amberley after the flood waters dropped in mid-February.{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=22}} In early February the north Queensland city of [[Cairns]] was threatened by [[Cyclone Yasi]], and the RAAF conducted two C-17 [[sortie]]s and two C-130 sorties to evacuate patients from [[Cairns Base Hospital]] on the night of 1/2 February.{{sfn|Hamilton|2011|p=21}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Defence Responds to Tropical Cyclone Yasi|url=http://www.defence.gov.au/media/DepartmentalTpl.cfm?CurrentId=11366|work=Media release|publisher=Department of Defence|accessdate=19 January 2013|date=2 February 2011}}{{dead link|date=November 2016}}</ref> After the cyclone passed over the Queensland coast, C-17s flew 200 tonnes of groceries into Cairns over a two-day period as part of [[Operation Yasi Assist]].{{sfn|Hamilton|2011|p=21}} No. 36 Squadron also contributed aircraft to the Australian response to the [[2011 Christchurch earthquake]] in late February, the C-17s flying [[urban search and rescue]] teams into the city from the 23rd of the month and evacuating Australian citizens on their return flights.{{sfn|Hamilton|2011|p=21}}
[[File:JGSDF truck being unloaded from a RAAF C-17.JPG|thumb|alt=Colour photo of a truck with a sign marked with Japanese characters over its cargo compartment driving away from the rear ramp of a grey aircraft at night.|A Japan Ground Self-Defense Force truck driving from A41-208 at Yokota Air Base after being flown from Okinawa]]

Three of the Australian C-17s were deployed to Japan following the [[2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami]] on 11 March. The first aircraft departed Australia two days after the disaster carrying 75 emergency response personnel, most of whom were members of [[Fire and Rescue NSW]]. After delivering these personnel to [[Yokota Air Base]], the C-17 remained in Japan to provide additional airlift to the [[Japan Self-Defense Forces]] (JSDF).{{sfn|Hamilton|2011|p=21}} In this role, the C-17 moved elements of the Japanese [[15th Brigade (Japan)|15th Brigade]] from [[Okinawa]] to [[Honshu]], and also transported supplies from a JSDF base in [[Hokkaido]].<ref name="Call from Japan">{{cite news|last=Oldaker|first=Aaron|author2=Hamilton, Eamon|title=Answering Call from Japan|url=http://digital.realviewtechnologies.com/?xml=defencenews_airforce.xml&iid=46744|accessdate=19 January 2013|newspaper=Air Force|date=31 March 2011|pages=2–3}}</ref> On 21/22 March, two other C-17s (including one temporarily brought back from the Middle East) flew a large water cannon system from RAAF Base Pearce in Western Australia to Yokota; owned by the [[Bechtel]] corporation, the water cannon formed part of the efforts to bring the badly damaged [[Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant]] under control.{{sfn|Hamilton|2011|p=21}} With the arrival of these aircraft, all three of the available Australian C-17s were in Japan (the fourth was still undergoing maintenance at Amberley).{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=22}} The RAAF maintained a C-17, two flight crews and support personnel in Japan until 25 March.{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=22}}<ref name="Call from Japan" /> By the end of this deployment the Australian aircraft had conducted 31 sorties and delivered 450 tonnes of cargo.{{sfn|Hamilton|2011|p=22}} No. 36 Squadron maintained a C-17 in the Middle East over most of this period.{{sfn|Hamilton|2011|p=22}} Also in March 2011, Smith stated that the Australian Government would probably provide C-17s to transport humanitarian supplies to Libya if the [[United Nations]] requested assistance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Thompson|first=Jeremy|title=Smith flags humanitarian role in Libya|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-03-10/smith-flags-humanitarian-role-in-libya/2662420|accessdate=24 March 2013|newspaper=ABC News|date=10 March 2011}}</ref>

The RAAF's C-17s responded to several other natural disasters between late 2011 and 2013. In October 2011 a Globemaster flew a water purification plant to Samoa, from where it was transported by [[Royal New Zealand Air Force]] aircraft to [[Tuvalu]].{{sfn|Pittaway|2012|p=22}} C-17s also transported supplies to Fiji and Samoa in December 2012 following [[Cyclone Evan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Humanitarian Support|url=http://www.airforce.gov.au/Operations/Humanitarian_support/?RAAF-hruuHkflEaNxq4BtnrEKSQz5XM3LaPec|publisher=Royal Australian Air Force|accessdate=24 March 2013}}</ref> In January 2013 two Globemasters flew power generators and transformers from Amberley to [[Hobart]] following the [[2013 Tasmanian bushfires|Tasmanian bushfires]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ADF providing assistance to Tasmanian bushfire victims|url=http://www.minister.defence.gov.au/2013/01/11/minister-for-defence-science-and-personnel-adf-providing-assistance-to-tasmanian-bushfire-victims/|work=Media release|publisher=The Hon. Warren Snowdon MP|date=11 January 2013|accessdate=24 March 2013}}</ref> Later that month C-17s were used to transport aviation fuel and other supplies into the Queensland town of [[Bundaberg]] after it was affected by [[January 2013 Eastern Australia floods|heavy flooding]].<ref name="Smith_Avalon_opening">{{cite web|title=Speech&nbsp;– Opening of the Avalon Airshow|url=http://www.minister.defence.gov.au/2013/02/26/minister-for-defence-speech-opening-of-the-avalon-airshow/|work=Media release|publisher=The Hon. Stephen Smith MP|date=26 February 2013|accessdate=24 March 2013}}</ref> In November 2013 a Globemaster flew a civilian medical team and its equipment from Australia to [[Cebu]] in the Philippines as part of the relief effort following [[Typhoon Haiyan]]; an RAAF C-130 subsequently transported the medical team from Cebu to [[Tacloban]] in the disaster zone.<ref>{{cite news|title=Help to Philippines|url=http://airforcenews.realviewdigital.com/?iid=84161#folio=2|accessdate=26 November 2013|newspaper=Air Force|date=21 November 2013|page=2}}</ref>

In July 2014, two Globemasters, several aircrews and maintenance personnel were deployed to [[Eindhoven Airport|Eindhoven Air Base]] in the Netherlands as part of the response to the shooting down of [[Malaysia Airlines Flight 17]] over the Ukraine.<ref name="SMH Relatives of the MH17 dead say goodbye">{{cite news|last1=Hatch|first1=Daniel|title=Relatives of the MH17 dead say goodbye as caskets are carried home from Ukraine|url=http://www.smh.com.au/world/relatives-of-the-mh17-dead-say-goodbye-as-caskets-are-carried-home-from-ukraine-20140729-zybr0.html|accessdate=5 November 2016|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=30 July 2014}}</ref> In conjunction with [[Royal Netherlands Air Force]] C-130s, the two aircraft ferried international police officers and their equipment between the Netherlands and [[Kharkiv]] in the Ukraine. They also flew the bodies of victims of the incident to the Netherlands.<ref name="SMH Relatives of the MH17 dead say goodbye" /> A third C-17 flew aircrew and equipment from Australia to the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite news|title=No rest for giants of the air|url=http://airforcenews.realviewdigital.com/?iid=99180#folio=4|accessdate=5 November 2016|work=Air Force|publisher=Department of Defence|date=14 August 2014|page=5}}</ref> This deployment was completed on 20 August 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thank you for Bring Them Home|url=http://airforcenews.realviewdigital.com/?iid=100141#folio=14|accessdate=5 November 2016|work=Air Force|publisher=Department of Defence|date=28 August 2014|page=15}}</ref>

The first flight by an RAAF C-17 to Antarctica was conducted in November 2015. The aircraft transported supplies for the [[Australian Antarctic Division]] from Hobart to [[Wilkins Runway]], and its crew practised evacuating casualties from Wilkins after the cargo was unloaded.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hunt|first1=Linda|title=Delivery for Antarctica: RAAF, Antarctic Division complete first air cargo mission to icy continent|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-11-22/raaf-involved-in-first-air-cargo-mission-to-antarctica/6961488|accessdate=22 November 2015|work=ABC News|date=22 November 2015}}</ref> This flight was reported to have been the first time the RAAF had flown missions to the Australian Antarctic Territory since the [[Antarctic Flight RAAF|Antarctic Flight]] was withdrawn in 1963.<ref>{{cite news|title=RAAF operates C-17 proof of concept flights to Antarctica|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2015/11/raaf-operates-c-17-proof-of-concept-flights-to-antarctica/|work=Australian Aviation|date=22 November 2015|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref> Further flights occurred in early 2016.<ref>{{cite media release |url=http://news.defence.gov.au/2016/02/20/antarctic-flights-prove-a-huge-success/|title=Antarctic flights prove a huge success|publisher=Department of Defence |date=20 February 2016 |accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref> A trial winter airdrop was also conducted at [[Casey Station]] in June that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=RAAF C-17 completes Antarctic winter airdrop|url=http://australianaviation.com.au/2016/06/raaf-c-17-completes-antarctic-winter-airdrop/|accessdate=13 November 2016|work=Australian Aviation|date=8 June 2016}}</ref>

